		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/?p=13534#comment-16990</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Love this lesson. Especially the clarification about playing octaves in a disco bass line context. I&#039;ve always struggled with trying to get up there on some of those lines even though I have massive hands with very long fingers (Boogie Oogie Oogie by Taste of Honey comes to mind). But what about faster lines like some of James Jamerson&#039;s lines? The intro  and first few phrases in the verse of Darling Dear are a good example. Lots of chromatic approach to octave parts and back to chromatics. My technique immediately goes out of the window when I attempt to play this because I&#039;m only focused on getting to the notes on time. When you come across those lines that are almost a barrage of notes on the lower part of the neck, are you still trying to do that 1-2-4 finger position, or are you going back to the finger per fret technique? (I&#039;m sure that the fingering that you choose is completely contextual so I guess I&#039;m only asking in context of Darling Dear).]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Love this lesson. Especially the clarification about playing octaves in a disco bass line context. I&#8217;ve always struggled with trying to get up there on some of those lines even though I have massive hands with very long fingers (Boogie Oogie Oogie by Taste of Honey comes to mind). But what about faster lines like some of James Jamerson&#8217;s lines? The intro  and first few phrases in the verse of Darling Dear are a good example. Lots of chromatic approach to octave parts and back to chromatics. My technique immediately goes out of the window when I attempt to play this because I&#8217;m only focused on getting to the notes on time. When you come across those lines that are almost a barrage of notes on the lower part of the neck, are you still trying to do that 1-2-4 finger position, or are you going back to the finger per fret technique? (I&#8217;m sure that the fingering that you choose is completely contextual so I guess I&#8217;m only asking in context of Darling Dear).</p>
]]></content:encoded>
