	<item>
		<title>By: Paul Danger Kile</title>
		<link>http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/technique/one-finger-per-fret-system.html#comment-16953</link>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Paul Danger Kile]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sat, 12 Mar 2016 00:13:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/?p=13534#comment-16953</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Scott.

For myself, on a 32&quot; scale bass, one finger per fret is fine.

There is an optimal amount of tension that the strings should have, but 34&quot; is longer than it needs to be, even with that in mind. I suspect that Leo Fender measured the scale length of a standup, and that was that.

I had a professor that insisted that I push with the tips of my finger bones, use one finger per fret, and not slide my hand ever. He believed that this would help me _avoid_ tendonitis. That guy was nuts. A full scale bass isn&#039;t a plastic-stringed classical guitar. Hopefully your help will keep other people from trying to do that.

My comments aren&#039;t practical advice, folks aren&#039;t going to run out and buy shorter bass, just because I like it. It&#039;s just food for thought.

Thank you for your help,
Paul]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Scott.</p>
<p>For myself, on a 32&#8243; scale bass, one finger per fret is fine.</p>
<p>There is an optimal amount of tension that the strings should have, but 34&#8243; is longer than it needs to be, even with that in mind. I suspect that Leo Fender measured the scale length of a standup, and that was that.</p>
<p>I had a professor that insisted that I push with the tips of my finger bones, use one finger per fret, and not slide my hand ever. He believed that this would help me _avoid_ tendonitis. That guy was nuts. A full scale bass isn&#8217;t a plastic-stringed classical guitar. Hopefully your help will keep other people from trying to do that.</p>
<p>My comments aren&#8217;t practical advice, folks aren&#8217;t going to run out and buy shorter bass, just because I like it. It&#8217;s just food for thought.</p>
<p>Thank you for your help,<br />
Paul</p>
]]></content:encoded>
